threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, no section header

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Detects a suspicious ELF binary with UPX compression
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This is a sample of the Mozi P2P botnet, targeting MIPS-based IoT devices. The malware spreads by exploiting numerous command injection vulnerabilities in web interfaces of various routers and IoT devices. It establishes persistence through startup scripts (e.g., /etc/rc.local, /etc/init.d/S95baby.sh), manipulates iptables to allow its P2P traffic, and disables system watchdogs. The presence of payload names like 'Mozi.m', 'Mozi.a' and protocol tags like '[/cnc]' and '[/idp]' are definitive indicators.
